**Summary of findings:**

- **Niyoga** = the ritual appointment of a widow (or childless wife) to a brother-in-law or sapiṇḍa kinsman, under strict conditions, solely to beget a son when the family line faces extinction. The son produced is called a *kṣetraja* son.

- **Manu** (Manusmṛti 9.59–68): Internally contradictory. Permits niyoga at 9.59–63 under tight rules (ghee, silence, night, one son only), then reverses at 9.64–68, calling it a "bestial law" nowhere sanctioned in Vedic marriage formulas, tracing it to the corrupt reign of King Vena.

- **Yājñavalkya** (Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.68–69): Cleanly permissive. States the same conditions (younger brother or sapiṇḍa/sagotra, elder authorization, ghee, fertile period, until conception only) without any subsequent self-condemnation.

- **Bṛhaspati** (1.25.16–17) resolves the Manu contradiction explicitly: "Though stated by Manu, niyoga was forbidden by him himself. Due to the decline of the age, it is impossible for all to perform it according to the rule"—attributing its impracticability to the degraded Kali Yuga.
